    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-09-27T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-09-27T04:00:00-05:00" n="620"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d620">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.9327/9–2748: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-09-27T18:00:00+09:00"
                            >September 27, 1948—6 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:22 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1773. Dr. Andrew Lin of Ministry of Communications has confirmed to Embassy
                    statement which he, as spokesman, made to local press, re Sino-Soviet air
                    agreement (reEmbtel 1765, September 25, repeated Shanghai as 852).</p>
                <p>Lin stated that impending renegotiation this agreement had no relation to
                    stoppage military airplane at Lanchow en route to Tihwa last month (see Deptel
                    1299, September 11). By devious and highly speculative circumlocution, Lin
                    implied that “possible reason for stopping plane which may have occurred to some
                    Chinese official in authority <pb facs="0757" n="747" xml:id="pg_747"/> was that
                    presence of Americans flying into Tihwa might complicate Chinese, relations with
                    Soviets.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 1773; repeated Shanghai 863.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
